To make a deeper analysis of the bonding nature of our titled compounds, the wave function obtained from a final Wien2k calculation at the optimal geometry has been analyzed in the critic program (version 1.0). Critic is a full-edged program for the topological analysis of solid-state electron densities.

This program uses the quantum theory of atom in molecule (QTAIM) to make a topological analysis of the electronic density $(\varrho)$ of a crystal. By means of QTAIM, we can automatically locate all critical points $\left(\mathrm{CP}^{\prime} \mathrm{s}\right)$ of the electronic density rising from a nil flux of the electron density gradient condition [27]. The procedure implemented in critic is to divide $\varrho$ into disjoint regions $\Omega$ (basins) through the real space approaches. Here, we can generate topological schemes in two or tridimensional plots. It is clearly shown from the topological distribution of the charge density in Figure 7A, that the charge distribution in the $\mathrm{SrZrO}_{3}$ compound is spherically symmetrical. This suggests that all electronic charges are localized around anions-a typical ionic bonding. The same trend is also displayed for the second compound with some small difference in the distribution of $\varrho$ due to the charge transfer, which differs in the two titled compounds (see Figure 7C). We also present in Figure 7B,D, the molecular graph of our two perovskites.

These plots were done following the character of Wyckoff's, bond CP and ring CP family [28]. The form of the atomic basin generated by the CCP point suggests that both $\mathrm{SrRhO}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{SrZrO}_{3}$ are belonging to the R11 family (see Figure 7B,D) [28]. Here, we can define a topological charge of each atomic basin. As results, $Q(\mathrm{Sr})=1.59$ electron, $Q(\mathrm{Rh})=1.47$ electron and $Q(\mathrm{O})=-1.05$ electron for SrRhO $_{3}$, and $Q(\mathrm{Sr})=1.61$ electron, $Q(\mathrm{Zr})=2.49$ electron and $Q(\mathrm{O})=-1.37$ electron for the $\mathrm{SrZrO}_{3}$ compound. When we compare these charges with the oxidation number corresponding to each of the atoms, we find that the charge transfer is mainly due to the strontium one, with an equal percentage of $80 \%$ in both perovskites. However, we note that replacing the cation $\mathrm{Rh}$ with electro-negativity of $2.2$ by the $\mathrm{Zr}$ one with low electro-negativity of $1.4$ has a negligible effect on the nature of the bonding. The $\mathrm{SrZrO}_{3}$ has a more ionic trend. However, even the constituent cations show different charge transfer $(\mathrm{Zr}$ and $\mathrm{Rh}$ are transferred by $62 \%$ and $37 \%)$ and each of them varies as strongly as the oxide ions. The latter adapt their charges according to electro-neutrality requirements. There is a second topological index that has been proposed as a global measurement of the degree of metallicity, the electron density flatness defined as $f=\frac{\rho_{c}^{\min }}{\rho_{b}^{\max }}$ where $\rho_{c}^{\min }$ is the minimal electron density found on the unit cell (it necessarily corresponds to a critical point) and $\rho_{b}^{\max }$ is the maximal electron density among bond critical points. This flatness has values close to one on common metallic compounds and close to zero on localized bonding compounds [29]. The delocalization of electrons (flatness) in the $\mathrm{SrRhO}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{SrZrO}_{3}$ compounds are respectively equal to $80.61 \%$ and $5.62 \%$. This suggests that the global chemical behavior of $\mathrm{SrRhO}_{3}$ is metallic, whereas $\mathrm{SrZrO}_{3}$ is nonmetallic. To go further in the characterization of the bonds nature of the titled compounds we have employed another tool named the electron localization function (ELF) [30], which is based on a measure of the likelihood of finding an electron in the neighborhood space of a reference electron located at a given point and with the same spin. Taking into account that the homogeneous electron gas has an ELF value of $0.5$, valence electrons of metals should deviate very slightly from this quantity. The ELF isosurfaces, as well as the one-dimensional projections of $\mathrm{Sr}-\mathrm{O}-\mathrm{Rh}$ and $\mathrm{Sr}-\mathrm{O}-\mathrm{Zr}$ bond paths of the investigated perovskites are depicted in Figure 8. It is strikingly clear from the plot that $\mathrm{O}-\mathrm{Zr}$ and $\mathrm{O}-\mathrm{Rh}$ are different. The integration of population on the ELF attractor of the $\mathrm{SrZrO}_{3}$ compound shows two types of $\mathrm{Zr}-\mathrm{O}$ bonds, the first one has ELF maxima equal to $0.78$ and the second to $0.83$; the former has the negligible population, but the latter has $0.95$ electrons. The integration gives a number of the delocalized attractor as lone pair bonds around the $\mathrm{Sr}$ and $\mathrm{Zr}$ cations; the population in this attractor varies from $1.4$ to $1.1$ electrons. Regarding the second compound $\left(\mathrm{SrRhO}_{3}\right)$, no $\mathrm{O}-\mathrm{Rh}$ bonds have been found, only delocalized lone pair ones with ELF maxima near to $0.5$ are reported. Here, we should emphasize that the delocalization of these attractors in the $\mathrm{SrRhO}_{3}$ compound provides a reliable measure of the delocalization of wave function and its localization in the $\mathrm{SrZrO}_{3}$ compound.\\
